I keep getting 500 Internal Server Error messages when trying to view commit info for commits in the Wiki history.

Page tells me to give you this ;) {{c21073b91ad144b39c0e4804d4f25e19}}

For those of you with permission to view private wiki commits, heres ONE of the URLs causing an issue: https://bitbucket.org/jduncanator/sh-it-v2/wiki/commits/c42c705f566433396e73ab7146eb0658ed5f32e3

Sometimes user commits to repo with different name and email address, usually after fresh install of git or mercurial. Let&#x27;s say new username in raw hg commit is {{someone <name@example.com>}}. If the user has not mapped this email to his account, Bitbucket website says {{Author not mapped to Bitbucket user.}} when viewing the commit.

Example API request which is affected by this issue: {{GET repositories/{accountname}/{repo_slug}/changesets/{raw_node}/}}

It has fields\\
{{"raw_author": "someone <name@example.com>"}}\\
{{"author": "someone"}}

If the user is not mapped to any Bitbucket account, it is possible the {{author}} field contains some existing username that has nothing to do with the commit. In these cases I&#x27;d like to have a new boolean field {{isUserMapped}} so I can either use the {{author}} when it&#x27;s mapped (for example to create a link to user account) or {{raw_author}} if user is not mapped.

The git import instructions displayed after creating a repo and selecting the option to push up an existing repo give the instructions:

{code}
#!bash

cd /path/to/my/repo
git remote add origin ssh://git@bitbucket.org/user/repository.git
git push -u origin --all   # to push up the repo for the first time
{code}

The instructions should also include:

{code}
#!bash

git push -u origin --tags # to push up all tags

{code}

so that tags are included, since is this is what most (unexperienced) git users will want. The two lines that push could be combined into:

{code}
#!bash

git push -u origin --all && git push -u origin --tags # to push up all branches and tags

{code}

*Hi guys!*\\
I am very glad that you are supporting Russian language. But there is a grammatical error in the translation. In the screenshot, the red text should be no double letters at the end.

*As it is at this moment:*

{code}
#!html
<div class="since-revision binary">
        <h5>Удаленн</h5>
</div>
{code}

*According to the rules of the Russian language:*

{code}
#!html
<h5>Удален</h5>
{code}

*And to be precise, it is better to write "file deleted":*

{code}
#!html
<h5>Файл удален</h5>
{code}

I&#x27;m writing custom solution to utilize POST Service at my server, but I need to know which branch was updated - I&#x27;m running applications out of master branch, doing development in develop or feature branches, and merging progress back to master - unfortunately, after merge from develop to master, data sent by POST Service looks like this:

{code}
&#x27;payload&#x27; => &#x27;{
	"repository": {
		"website": "",
		"fork": false,
		"name": "YYY",
		"scm": "git",
		"owner": "XXX",
		"absolute_url": "/XXX/YYY/",
		"slug": "YYY",
		"is_private": true
	},
	"truncated": false,
	"commits": [],
	"canon_url": "https://bitbucket.org",
	"user": "XXX"
}&#x27;,
{code}

I don&#x27;t want to pull from origin after every commit, only when master branch is changed, but with empty &#x27;commits&#x27; array, I am out of luck. Is there anything I can change in git configuration to see commits in POST Service payload after merge & push, please?

